# Way of the Vigil
*A Monastic Tradition for 2014 Monk*

Monks of the Vigil stand watch at the thin places -- hell mouths, planar breaches, sealed gates, and sanctified ground where something on the other side wants through. Their monasteries are founded on such sites, and their training produces wardens: ascetics who learn that a disciplined body is itself a ward, every kata a rite of protection, every breath an act of devotion.

Most Vigil monasteries stand against the Lower Planes, and their monks count fiends as their oldest enemies. But the tradition is older than any one faith. Orders exist that keep vigil against the meddling of celestials, the intrusion of the fey, or the hunger of aberrations -- each shaped by its own doctrine, each certain its watch is the one that matters. What unites them is the vow: the door stays shut, and the warden stands before it.

No warden stands alone. A vigil is kept in shifts, shoulder to shoulder, and the first lesson of the tradition is that the watcher who guards only themselves has already failed. Those who leave the monastery carry the vow with them -- wherever a Vigil monk travels, their companions become their fellow keepers, and the ward extends to all who stand the watch beside them.

